<section aria-label="How simulators are used" style="margin-top: 32px;">
  <div class="prose">
    <h2>How to use a simulator productively</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Read the briefing.</strong> Each scenario has a hazard profile, a budget, and constraints. Skim them before placing anything.</li>
      <li><strong>Predict before you run.</strong> Write or voice-note what you expect to happen and why. This is the entry that turns a sim run into evidence.</li>
      <li><strong>Run it.</strong> The disaster plays out. Population saved, critical infrastructure intact, score, grade — all logged.</li>
      <li><strong>Reflect after.</strong> What actually happened vs. what you predicted? Where did your model of the geology break down?</li>
      <li><strong>Iterate.</strong> Change ONE thing, predict again, run. Three iterations minimum for the portfolios.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Need help thinking through a design decision? Open the <a href="/ai-partners/engineering-coach/">Engineering Coach</a>. Stuck on why a hazard is what it is? Try the <a href="/ai-partners/plate-tectonics-tutor/">Plate Tectonics Tutor</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>
